cache vs persist
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pw1vn82wEBE&list=PLTsNSGeIpGnFiErPovNizG_2IP2RvrgnK&index=45
Chaliye, main aapko bilkul usi flow aur tone mein samjhata hoon jaise video mein explain kiya gaya hai using HinEnglish.

### 1. Basic Concept aur Memory Management Recap
Sabse pehle, Caching kya hai? Ye ek optimization technique hai jo hamare **intermediate results** ko store karke rakhta hai.

Isko samajhne ke liye humne Spark Memory Management (Executor wala part) ko recap kiya tha. Executor ke container ke andar teen cheezein hoti hain: User Memory, Spark Memory, aur Reserved Memory. Spark Memory ke andar do pools hote hain:
1.  **Storage Memory Pool**
2.  **Executor Memory Pool**

Jab bhi hum data ko cache karte hain, toh wo data sirf aur sirf **Storage Memory Pool** mein jaake store hota hai. Agar Execution pool (jahan calculation hoti hai) ko memory ki zaroorat padti hai, toh wo Storage pool se data ko "evict" (udha) kar sakta hai LRU (Least Recently Used) fashion mein.

### 2. Example: Caching ki zaroorat kyun hai? (The "Why")
Ab main aapko code example se samjhata hoon ki humein iski actual need kyun padti hai.

Imagine kijiye humne ek code likha:
*   Pehle `df` banaya ek file load karke.
*   Phir `df2` banaya jisme `df` ko join kiya `df1` ke saath.
*   Phir `df4` banaya jisme usi `df` ko join kiya `df3` ke saath.

Spark mein DataFrames immutable hote hain aur operations **Lazily Evaluated** hote hain. `df` jo hai wo Executor ki "short-lived memory" mein banta hai.
*   Jab `df2` ke liye action call hoga, `df` calculate hoga aur use ho jayega.
*   Lekin jab `df4` banega, toh kyunki `df` memory se chala gaya tha (short-lived tha), Spark wapas jayega aur DAG (Directed Acyclic Graph) ke through `df` ko **re-calculate** karega.

Isse hamara time waste hoga. Isiliye hum `df.cache()` use karte hain. Jaise hi hum `.cache()` likhte hain, data short-lived memory se uth kar **Storage Memory Pool** mein aa jata hai jo long-term ke liye rehta hai (jab tak application chal rahi hai). Isse baar-baar re-calculation nahi karni padti.

### 3. Partition aur Storage Logic
Yahan ek bahut important interview question banta hai. Maan lijiye aapke paas 2GB ka storage pool hai lekin data 2.5GB ka hai.
*   Spark kabhi bhi **half partition** store nahi karega. Agar wo 12 partitions store kar pa raha hai aur 13th partition aadha fit ho raha hai, toh wo us aadhe ko store nahi karega.
*   Jo partitions fit nahi honge, unhein ya toh disk pe bheja jayega (agar level waisa hai) ya phir unhein **re-calculate** kiya jayega.
*   Agar koi partition galti se **lost** ho jata hai, toh DAG usse wapas re-calculate kar leta hai.

### 4. Cache vs Persist
Bahut baar pucha jata hai: **Difference between Cache and Persist?**
Seedha sa answer hai: `Persist` hi main function hai. `Cache` bas `Persist` ke upar likha gaya ek wrapper hai.
*   **Cache:** Jab hum `.cache()` call karte hain, toh wo internal `.persist()` ko call karta hai ek fixed default storage level ke saath (Video mein bataya gaya hai ki default `MEMORY_AND_DISK` set hota hai).
*   **Persist:** `.persist()` humein flexibility deta hai ki hum arguments pass kar sakein, yaani hum apna **Storage Level** khud choose kar sakte hain.

### 5. Storage Levels (In-Depth)
Humne alag-alag storage levels discuss kiye jo aap `.persist()` mein use kar sakte hain:

*   **MEMORY_ONLY:**
    *   Ye data ko sirf RAM mein rakhta hai **Deserialized** form mein.
    *   **Advantage:** Process fast hota hai.
    *   **Disadvantage:** Memory utilization bahut high hoti hai.
*   **MEMORY_AND_DISK:**
    *   Pehle RAM mein try karega. Agar RAM full ho gayi, toh bacha hua data **Disk** pe bhej dega.
    *   Disk pe data hamesha **Serialized** form mein rehta hai.
    *   Disk se read/write karne mein time lagta hai aur CPU usage high ho sakta hai kyunki data ko wapas deserialize karna padega.
*   **DISK_ONLY:**
    *   Sara data disk pe rahega. Ye slow hota hai.
*   **_SER (Serialized) levels (e.g., MEMORY_ONLY_SER):**
    *   Data ko byte stream (Serialized) mein rakhta hai.
    *   **Benefit:** Space bachta hai (e.g., 5GB data compress hoke kam jagah lega).
    *   **Drawback:** Jab use karna hoga toh CPU usage high hoga kyunki De-serialization karna padega.
    *   *Note:* Video ke end mein bataya tha ki ye Serialization wala feature mainly **Java aur Scala** mein kaam karta hai, Python mein directly aise nahi dikhta.
*   **_2 (Replication) levels (e.g., MEMORY_ONLY_2):**
    *   Ye data ki 2 copies rakhta hai alag-alag nodes pe.
    *   Agar ek worker node down ho gaya, toh doosre node se data le lega taaki re-calculation na karna pade.

### 6. Practical Demo aur "Show" vs "Count" ka catch
Humne code run karke bhi dekha Spark UI pe.
*   Jab humne `df.cache()` ke baad sirf `df.show()` kiya: Spark UI ke Storage tab mein sirf **1 Partition** cache hua dikha. Kyunki Spark intelligent hai, usne dekha ki `show()` ke liye sirf top rows chahiye, toh poora data kyu cache karein?.
*   Jab humne `df.count()` kiya: Tab saare partitions (4 partitions) cache huye kyunki count ke liye poora data chahiye tha.
*   UI mein humne dekha ki **Serialized (Disk)** data ka size (1.2 MB) kam tha as compared to **Deserialized (Memory)** data (3.3 MB).

### 7. Unpersist aur Conclusion
Last mein, agar data ko memory se hatana hai toh kya karein?
Simple, `df.unpersist()` method call kar dijiye, data cache se hatt jayega.

Toh ye thi saari kahani Cache aur Persist ki. Maine koshish ki hai ki koi bhi detail miss na ho. Agar aap ye saare points (Intermediate results, Lazy evaluation example, Partition logic, Storage levels difference) interview mein bol denge, toh I don't think koi aapko phasa payega.

**Link:** Description mein documentation ka link mil jayega, wahan se aur detail padh lena.

Chaliye, milte hain agle video mein. Tab tak ke liye, Bye Bye!

